In New Yorks primary these rounds of elimination will continue until there are two candidates left even if a candidate collects more than 50 of votes before the very end

Whats more likely to happen is well see candidates be eliminated over five rounds of counting Each round the candidate with the fewest votes gets cut then those votes are reallocated to the voters nextranked candidate

Once all the votes are in there are two potential outcomes The first is that someone wins outright with a majority of votes in the first round But few think that will happen in the crowded mayors race
However dont rank the same candidate more than once it will count for only one vote Nor should you rank more than one candidate in the same spot which will invalidate your ballot

You can still vote for just one candidate but ranking multiple candidates stretches your vote further and wont hurt your favorite If your firstchoice candidate is eliminated your vote goes to your second choice It never hurts to have a backup
